programme.desc: The last AFL-NFL game before the merger. The Chiefs dominate the Vikings giving them their first Super Bowl title. From Jan. 11, 1970 at Tulane Stadium in New Orleans.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: The Colts beat the Cowboys 16-13 on rookie kicker Jim O'Brien's 32-yard field goal in the final five seconds. Chuck Howley earns the game's MVP award. From Jan. 17, 1971 at Orange Bowl in Miami.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: The Cowboys rush for a record 252 yards and their defense limited the Dolphins to a low of 185 yards while not permitting a touchdown for the first time in Super Bowl history. From Jan. 16, 1972 at Tulane Stadium in New Orleans.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: The Dolphins beat the Washington Redskins 14-7 to become the only team in NFL history to complete a perfect season (17-0). From Jan. 14, 1973 at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum in Los Angeles.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: The Dolphins defeat the Vikings by a score of 24-7 to become the second team in NFL history to win back-to-back Super Bowls. From Jan. 13, 1974 at Rice Stadium in Houston.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: Steelers running back Franco Harris rushes for 158 yards and a touchdown earning Super Bowl MVP honors as the Steelers beat the Vikings 16-6. From Jan. 12, 1975 at Tulane Stadium in New Orleans.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: Lynn Swann is named Super Bowl MVP as the Steelers win their second straight NFL Championship. From Jan. 18, 1976 at Orange Bowl in Miami.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: Under head coach John Madden, the Raiders win their first Super Bowl in franchise history by defeating the Vikings 32-14. From Jan. 9, 1977 at Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: Roger Staubach and the "Doomsday Defense" of Dallas defeat the Denver Broncos and win their fourth Super Bowl. This Super Bowl was the first one to be played in a domed stadium. From Louisiana Superdome in New Orleans.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: Steelers become first team in NFL history to win three Super Bowls, defeating the Cowboys 35-31. Terry Bradshaw is the MVP after passing for record 4 touchdowns and 318 yards.

programme.title: Lightning Strikes Twice (1951)
programme.desc: A Texas rancher acquitted of his wife's murder by one juror's vote falls in love with an actress, and a complex web of jealousy and attraction ensues.

programme.title: The Big Combo (1955)
programme.desc: A police officer is obsessed with bringing down a gangster in part because he loves the bad man's girlfriend. When the moll provides the cop with a new lead, he gets close to toppling the syndicate man, who is also dealing with dissension within his own ranks.

programme.title: High Wall (1947)
programme.desc: A World War II veteran suffering from a recurring brain injury teams with a woman psychiatrist to prove himself innocent of his wife's murder.

programme.title: Lady in the Lake (1946)
programme.desc: Subjective camera work allows the viewer to see this film-noir mystery transpire through the eyes of a private detective who finds murder while investigating the case of a missing woman. The script was adapted from the Raymond Chandler novel; and Robert Montgomery directed and stars as private eye Philip Marlowe.

programme.title: Whirlpool (1949)
programme.desc: A bogus therapist hypnotizes a famous psychoanalyst's wife, who's a kleptomaniac, and sets her up to take the fall for a murder.

programme.title: The Man Who Watched the Trains Go By (1953)
programme.desc: A business owner and his clerk go head to head over the company funds.

programme.title: T-Men (1947)
programme.desc: Semi-documentary about two Treasury agents working to take down a counterfeiting ring. Partners O'Brien and Genaro go undercover to bring the ruthless criminals to justice.

programme.title: The House on 92nd Street (1945)
programme.desc: Nazi spies in America recruit a German-American college student, who promptly goes to the FBI. The Feds convince him to be come a double agent, and help them find the leader of this clan of saboteurs.

programme.title: The Snake Pit (1948)
programme.desc: A seemingly normal married woman behaves so erratically that her husband asks that she get professional help, whereupon she is confined to a state hospital; she is well-treated by her kindly doctor, but abused by patients and matrons alike. A Best Picture nominee.

programme.title: I Was a Communist for the FBI (1951)
programme.desc: Story of Matt Cvetic (Frank Lovejoy), who joined the Reds to gather information for the FBI. Moves fast. Eve: Dorothy Hart. Mason: Philip Carey. Blandon: James Millican. Krowley: Richard Webb. Gerhardt Eisler: Konstantin Shayne.

programme.title: Whiplash (1948)
programme.desc: An invalid, disabled in the ring, lives vicariously through his wife's paramour by training him to be a championship boxer.

programme.title: It Happens Every Spring (1949)
programme.desc: A professor becomes a Major League pitching ace after he invents some gunk that makes baseballs avoid bats.

programme.title: Go for Broke! (1951)
programme.desc: WWII action with the Nisei 442nd Regimental Combat Team. Good, despite some lapses. Van Johnson, Gianna Maria Canale, Lane Nakano, George Niki, Warner Anderson. Directed by Robert Pirosh.

programme.title: The Razor's Edge (1946)
programme.desc: A disillusioned World War I veteran moves to Paris, where he has his heart broken by the woman he loves when she marries another man for his wealth, so he goes off on a journey of self-fulfillment and to seek out the meaning of life in India.

programme.title: The Long Voyage Home (1940)
programme.desc: The lives of the crew who live aboard the freighter Glencairn are followed as they drink, womanize, fight and bond, sometimes searching for ways to cure boredom, and sometimes facing life or death situations.

programme.title: Guadalcanal Diary (1943)
programme.desc: One soldier chronicles his experiences at Guadalcanal, exploring the battles and lives of other soldiers as well as his own.

programme.title: D-Day, the Sixth of June (1956)
programme.desc: Stirring account of the Normandy Invasion. Robert Taylor, Dana Wynter, Richard Todd, Edmond O'Brien. Boyce: Jerry Paris. Directed by Henry Koster.

programme.title: A Midnight Clear (1992)
programme.desc: About the final days of World War II, from the viewpoint of a young sergeant.

programme.title: Perry Mason: The Case of the Sinister Spirit (1987)
programme.desc: The attorney (Raymond Burr) represents a publisher (Robert Stack) accused of murdering a writer at a haunted hotel. Andrew: Dwight Schultz. Susan: Kim Delaney. Paul: William Katt. Light: Dennis Lipscomb. Maura: Leigh Taylor-Young. Sayer: Jack Bannon. Della: Barbara Hale. Richard Lang directed.

programme.title: Bus Stop (1956)
programme.desc: Adaptation of the William Inge play about a pathetic saloon singer who takes off for L.A. but is pursued by a lovesick Montana cowboy, who kidnaps her to bring her back to his hometown. As the cowboy, Don Murray was nominated for a Best Supporting Actor Oscar.

programme.title: Pit Stop (1967)
programme.desc: A look at the exploits of a driver who would do anything to win everything.

programme.title: Fast Company (1979)
programme.desc: A champion drag racer clashes with the unscrupulous oil-company executive who sponsors his team.

programme.title: Macon County Line (1974)
programme.desc: In 1954 Georgia, a sheriff's wife is brutally murdered, and the blood-thirsty widower suspects two drifters and their hitchhiking friend. The drifters are in the wrong place at the wrong time, and are forced to defend themselves.

programme.title: Blondie's Hero (1950)
programme.desc: Dagwood enters the Army Reserve and Blondie visits only to discover that he has caused all sorts of problems which lead to numerous conflicts.

programme.title: Sherlock Holmes in Washington (1943)
programme.desc: A match cover with a concealed microfilm passes in and out of enemy hands. Basil Rathbone, Nigel Bruce, Marjorie Lord. Stanley: George Zucco. Pete: John Archer. Easter: Henry Daniell. Howe: Don Terry. Familiarly interesting. Roy William Neill directed.

programme.title: The Adventures of Young Indiana Jones
programme.desc: Young Indy has a spirited encounter in India with a youthful Jiddu Krishnamurti; and in China, he becomes ill with typhoid fever and is saved by ancient medical practices.

programme.title: Take Her, She's Mine (1963)
programme.desc: After his beatnik daughter, in Paris on an art scholarship, appears on a magazine cover, a respected Board of Education president is asked to resign; and he gets into his own predicaments when he flies to France to insist she come home.

programme.title: Movie, Movie (1978)
programme.desc: Stanley Donen directed this spoof of Hollywood musicals and prizefight dramas. George C. Scott, Trish Van Devere, Eli Wallach, Art Carney, Red Buttons. Joey: Harry Hamlin. Trixie: Barbara Harris. Dick/Johnny: Barry Bostwick.

programme.desc: Bridget Jones, now a fortysomething news producer, discovers that she's pregnant, but she isn't sure if the father is her on-and-off boyfriend Mark Darcy or new love interest Jack Qwant.

programme.title: Gentleman's Agreement (1947)
programme.desc: The experiences of a journalist who pretends to be Jewish to gather data for an exposé on anti-Semitism, and the hatred he is subjected to that takes its toll on his personal life.
